'''Jill Wisoff''' is an American [[filmmaker]], [[performer]], [[actress]] and [[film composer]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/person/203540/Jill-Wisoff|title=Movies|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nywift.org/article.aspx?id=2543|title=NYWIFT Screening Series: Living in the Aftermath of 9/11|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> best known for original music and songs in ''[[Welcome to the Dollhouse]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://history.sundance.org/films/1355|title=Sundance Institute|website=history.sundance.org|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> [[Todd Solondz]]'s critically acclaimed 1996 [[Sundance Film Festival]] Grand Jury Prize winner.
==Works==
Her original musical scores can be heard in such representative work as ''Second Skin'' by filmmaker Amy Talkington,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcomet.com/movie/Second_Skin-758614/cast_credits.html|title=Mcoment.com|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> a 1999 Sundance Film Festival selection that sold to television worldwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amytalkington.com/projects/second-skin/|title=amy talkington|website=amytalkington.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> For producer Alan Sacks, she scored [[Melissa Gilbert]]'s 1996 directorial debut,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/person/71139%7C0/Melissa-Gilbert/|title=Overview for Melissa Gilbert|website=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> ''Me and My Hormones'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/471763/Me-and-My-Hormones/|title=Me and My Hormones (1996) - Overview - TCM.com|website=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> an ABC Afterschool Special; in ''[[Smart House (film)|Smart House]]'', a 1999 TV movie for Disney Channel directed by [[LeVar Burton]], she co-wrote the song "The House is Jumpin'"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.aol.com/song/various-artists/house-is-jumpin/2788740|title=AOL Music|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> with [[Barry Goldberg]] and Joel Diamond, and contributed additional score.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcm.com/tcmdb/title/475316/Smart-House/|title=Smart House (1999) - Overview - TCM.com|website=Turner Classic Movies|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> Working with filmmaker Adam Goldstein and produced by [[William Kennedy (author)|William Kennedy]], she scored ''Woman Found Dead in Elevator'' (2000), based on a story by Ruth Tarson with special material provided by [[Hunter S. Thompson]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.entgroup.cn/551002/fullcredits/|title=Woman Found Dead in Elevator Cast and Crew,Boxoffice-EntGroup|website=english.entgroup.cn|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> and starring ''[[Wit (play)|Wit]]'' Broadway star [[Kathleen Chalfant]] and<ref>{{cite web|url=http://everything2.com/title/George+Plimpton|title=George Plimpton - Everything2.com|website=everything2.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> [[George Plimpton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soundtrack.net/composers/database/?id=775|title=Latest Composer and Music Supervisor Assignment|website=www.soundtrack.net|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>
==Biography== Born in Queens,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creatingkarma.com/|title=Creatingkarma.com|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> New York, her training in composition began while a student in the [[Manhattan School of Music]] Preparatory Division and later at [[Bennington College]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sonyclassics.com/welcome/crew/wisoff.html|title=Jill Wisoff|website=www.sonyclassics.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> under [[Vivian Fine]] and [[Henry Brant]]. She directed, composed music and performed in stock and off-off Broadway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theaterforthenewcity.net/history1970.htm|title=Theater for the New City - Production History, 1970 - 1979|website=theaterforthenewcity.net|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> As a musician, she performed as lead guitarist for the all-girl reggae band, Steppin' Razor, produced by [[Chris Spedding]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chrisspedding.com/session/ca/ca.htm|title=The Con Artists index|website=www.chrisspedding.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> who later produced her own band, The Con Artists, some songs of which are included in the Welcome to the Dollhouse soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chrisspedding.com/session/ca/ca2.htm|title=original soundtrack / Chris Spedding - Welcome To The Dollhouse|website=www.chrisspedding.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> She later toured as bassist in Europe and the U.S. for the legendary [[Johnny Thunders]] as a member of his last band, The Oddballs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetrock.com/music/artist/johnny-thunders/bio/|title=Planetrock.com|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> Between tours, she completed reshoots co-starring as Sharon opposite Todd Solondz's Ira<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ifc.com/fix/2010/07/your-early-work-fear-anxiety-d|title=Your Early Work: “Fear, Anxiety & Depression”|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> in his lesser known first feature film, ''[[Fear, Anxiety & Depression]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cineplex.com/Movies/Cast-Archives/3539208/Sam/Photo.aspx?id=416242|title=Cineplex.com - Sam|website=www.cineplex.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> theatrically released in 1989 through the Samuel Goldwyn Company, for which she was cited for her "comic flair" in Caryn James' review in The New York Times.<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|title=Fear Anxiety and Depression (1989) Review/Film; Spoofing the Unity of Art and Agony|first=Caryn|last=James|date=December 8, 1989|url=https://movies.nytimes.com/movie/review?res=950DEEDA1E39F93BA35751C1A96F948260|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> She made her directorial debut with the feature comedy film, ''[[Creating Karma]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laweekly.com/2009-10-15/film-tv/movie-reviews-black-dynamite-the-stepfather-law-abiding-citizen/|title=Movie Reviews: Black Dynamite, The Stepfather, Law Abiding Citizen|first=LA|last=Weekly|date=14 October 2009|publisher=|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> theatrically released<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laemmle.com/viewmovie.php?mid=5319|title=Welcome to Laemmle Theatres - Laemmle.com|website=www.laemmle.com|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref> in 2009. Her documentary produced with Harris F.B. Salomon, ''The Day After'', she completed in 2010 with footage she shot at Ground Zero on September 12, 2001. Following a screening series by New York Women in Film and Television called ''Life in the Aftermath of 9/11'', it was invited to be included in the memorial library collection of the naval ship [[USS New York (LPD-21)|USS New York]], and the archives of the Tribute WTC Visitor Center. She also co-wrote "The Collected Letters of Snaps" with Salomon. The adventures of a retired greyhound racing dog in New York.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mca-marines.org/gazette/uss-new-york-memorial-library|title=USS New York Memorial Library - Marine Corps Association|website=www.mca-marines.org|accessdate=1 August 2018}}</ref>
