[[File:Mappa Soleto.jpg|thumb]] The '''Soleto Map''' is a possibly ancient [[map]], which depicts [[Salento]] on a small piece of [[ostrakon]] derived from a [[terracotta]] vase.<ref>Summary of 2005 colloquium on Soleto Map an Moonpellier, France: [https://web.archive.org/web/20080307125758/http://www.unc.edu/awmc/soletomap.html A New Ancient Map? The Salentine peninsula in the 5th century BC] (page taken down: link from Wayback Machine).</ref> However, while the ostrakon is undoubtedly ancient, doubts have been raised about the age of the map.
==Background== The map was discovered in [[Soleto]] (southern [[Italy]]) by [[Belgium|Belgian]] archaeologist Thierry van Compernolle of [[Montpellier University]] on August 21, 2003.<ref>Newspaper article on the discovery of the map:[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/main.jhtml?xml=/news/2005/11/18/wmap18.xml Telegraph - Archaeologists find western world's oldest map]</ref> The map itself dates back to 500 BC and contains letters derived from a [[Greek script]]. The languages expressed on the map are both [[Ancient Greek language|Greek]] and [[Messapian language|Messapian]]. Moreover, the Soleto Map describes the city of [[Taranto]] (called Taras), as well as other cities of Salento such as Soleto, [[Santa Maria di Leuca|Leuca]], [[Ugento]], and [[Otranto]]. The map went on public display in 2005 at the Archaeological National Museum of Taranto.
==Controversy== Even though the Soleto Map is considered the oldest map in [[Western culture|Western civilization]], there are allegations that it is a forgery.<ref>One of those allegations is here: http://www.maproomblog.com/2006/02/is_the_soleto_map_a_forgery.php (read on November 26th, 2014)</ref> In the January/February 2006 issue of the [[Netherlands|Dutch]] newspaper ''Geschiedenis Magazine'', Dutch [[archaeologist]] Douwe Yntema of Vrije University in [[Amsterdam]] found the authenticity of the map questionable.<ref>See this article for more discussion on this controversy:[http://mailman.geo.uu.nl/pipermail/maphist/2006-February/006646.html Maphist - 'World's oldest map' a fake? (Soleto map 5th century BC)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713101518/http://mailman.geo.uu.nl/pipermail/maphist/2006-February/006646.html |date=2007-07-13 }}</ref> Even though the ostrakon is ancient, the authenticity of the engravings are dubious.<ref>See this article for more discussion on this controversy:[http://mailman.geo.uu.nl/pipermail/maphist/2006-February/006646.html Maphist - 'World's oldest map' a fake? (Soleto map 5th century BC)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713101518/http://mailman.geo.uu.nl/pipermail/maphist/2006-February/006646.html |date=2007-07-13 }}</ref> According to Yntema, the map looks like a school atlas with placenames engraved with "north" at the top. Moreover, the Soleto Map shows the towns as points rather than house symbols found on other ancient maps. Finally, the engravings follow the precise borders of the ostrakon itself, which can lead anyone to interpret the Soleto Map as being made after the terracotta vase was first broken.<ref>Claus Moser, [http://www.kartentisch.de/?p=70 (in German)] at kartentisch.de</ref>
